content:
The swarm runtime should emit MAP sync messages on its own MAP endpoint after minimem or skill-tree push operations.

```
swarm.on('minimem:pushed', (result) => {
  swarm.map.broadcast({
    type: 'memory:sync',
    resource_id: result.resource_id,
    agent_id: swarm.agent_id,
    commit_hash: result.commit_hash,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
  });
});

swarm.on('skilltree:pushed', (result) => {
  swarm.map.broadcast({
    type: 'skill:sync',
    resource_id: result.resource_id,
    agent_id: swarm.agent_id,
    commit_hash: result.commit_hash,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
  });
});
```

The swarm needs to know the `resource_id` for each local memory directory / skill repo. This mapping is part of the swarm's configuration (which local dirs correspond to which OpenHive resources).

An agent/swarm can have multiple memory and skill repos — each maps to a different `resource_id`.

Depends on [[i-5nl8]] for message type definitions.
Implements [[s-78fe]].

When a swarm receives a `memory:sync` or `skill:sync` message (relayed by OpenHive), it should trigger the appropriate tool operation:

```
swarm.map.on('memory:sync', (msg) => {
  if (msg.agent_id === swarm.agent_id) return;  // ignore own messages
  const resource = swarm.getSubscribedResource(msg.resource_id);
  if (!resource) return;
  swarm.minimem.pull(resource.git_remote_url);
  swarm.minimem.reindex(resource.local_dir);
});

swarm.map.on('skill:sync', (msg) => {
  if (msg.agent_id === swarm.agent_id) return;
  const resource = swarm.getSubscribedResource(msg.resource_id);
  if (!resource) return;
  swarm.skillTree.refreshRemote(resource.remote_name);
});
```

The swarm maintains a mapping of subscribed `resource_id` → local directory / remote name so it knows where to pull content into.

Depends on [[i-cvge]] (OpenHive relay must work to deliver messages).
Implements [[s-78fe]].

feedback.content:
Covered by `MapSyncClient` in `src/map/sync-client.ts`:
- `onMemorySync(handler)` / `onSkillSync(handler)` — register callbacks for incoming sync messages
- `handleIncomingSync()` — filters by agent_id (ignores own), matches `resource_id` to `subscribed_resources`, dispatches to registered handlers
- `connectToHub()` — connects to OpenHive's WebSocket endpoint to receive relayed messages
- Reconnection with exponential backoff

Usage:
```typescript
const client = new MapSyncClient({ agent_id, hub_ws_url, subscribed_resources: [...] });
client.onMemorySync((msg, resource) => {
  minimem.pull(resource.git_remote_url);
  minimem.reindex(resource.local_dir);
});
client.onSkillSync((msg, resource) => {
  skillTree.refreshRemote(resource.local_dir);
});
client.start();
```

content:
Since MAP messages are fire-and-forget with no delivery guarantees, swarms need a polling loop to catch up on missed messages (e.g., after being offline).

```
swarm.startPollingLoop({
  interval: 60_000,  // configurable
  onUpdate: (resource, newCommit) => {
    // Same pull logic as receiving a MAP message
  }
});
```

Polling options:
- **Git remote ref check** — compare local HEAD vs remote HEAD for each subscribed resource
- **OpenHive's existing `POST /resources/:id/check-updates`** — checks remote git ref and returns whether there are updates

The swarm owns its polling cadence. This is independent of MAP message delivery and works even if OpenHive is also offline.

Implements [[s-78fe]].

feedback.content:
Implemented polling fallback in `MapSyncClient`:
- Added `PollChecker` callback type — consumer provides a function that checks resources for updates (git ls-remote, OpenHive API, etc.)
- `runPollCycle()` calls the checker, synthesizes `MapSyncMessage` objects for each update, dispatches through the same `onMemorySync`/`onSkillSync` handlers as real-time messages
- Initial poll runs on `start()` to catch up immediately after coming online
- Guard against concurrent poll cycles via `this.polling` flag

Usage:
```typescript
const client = new MapSyncClient({
  agent_id: 'agent-a',
  subscribed_resources: [...],
  poll_interval_ms: 60_000,
  poll_checker: async (resources) => {
    // Check git remote refs, return those with new commits
    return [{ resource_id: 'res_abc', commit_hash: 'new123' }];
  },
});
```
